content.description: Fun little slab right off the road. Multiple variations can be done with varying difficulties. The center problem climbs like a mini 'Starface', minimal holds on great rock. Worth doing!
content.location: Across the road from Titanic Boulder, on the right side. Look for the obvious triangular shaped boulder.

content.description:
Overseeing the landscape is the patriarch of Mt. Woodson, The Uncertainty Principle.  Some despise it while some revere it, but all respect it!  From the gate, it is located about a half mile up the road, capturing the interest of all who pass by it.  Continue up the road past the roadside route

Rock The Boat

and take a left turn trail to easily access.  The route involves stepping off a boulder on the right side climbing straight up to the top.  The crux is getting past the initial moves.

Highly recommended.
content.protection: TR, bolts.  Set-up is via a two bolt lead up the north face (low-angled face in the picture).

content.description: The most often tried problem on this boulder is a groove that has a nice knob about chest height, but minimal feet.  Its about a foot off the road, facing the road, just before the right hairpin turn to Uncertainty Principle
A right traversing layback/undercling with slippery feet and gradually slippier hands.
content.location: Just past Pickpocket and off to the left of the road.  A huge right leaning "flake" just about visible from the road.

content.description: The route on the right of the A3 RURP face behind Uncertainty Principal.

Originally an aid route, this is one of the few bolted lead routes at Mt. Woodson.  Just past the Uncertainty Principle switchback on one's left is this route.  If you look right from this one, you'd see the Robbins Crack.
A few walking strides past "Driving South" is this fun face climb.  On the right side of the road, this face features softball size dents in the rock with the crux coming a bit short of top.

These couple of roadside boulders have several topropes or boulder problems that range from 5.8 to 5.12 (Woodward Direct).  Thankfully much of the paint that was dumped on them so many years ago has worn off, via nature.
content.location: At the Uncertainty Principle switchback, these are found on the lefthand side, just steps off the road.

content.description: Traverse the Painted Boulder by using the flakes coming out of the ground of the boulder for feet. Climb either direction until no more flakes. Great warm-up.
content.location: On the Painted Boulder, just a few feet off the road at the switchback in the Uncertainty Principle Area. The climb is facing the road using the flakes jutting out of the ground.

content.description: This face route climbs the boulder on the lower left of U.P. facing south.  It starts in a bit of an alcove moving up and right before finishing up and left.  A knob move about 1/3 of the way up is the key.
Lieback from a bottoming groove to a big righthand huck to the rounded corner and power over the top
content.location: From Bobby Brown arete turn and look due west. You will see a rounded tooth with a prominent seam that ends short of the top.

content.description: Sit start matched on a small rail on the left side of the boulder.  One hard move to the lip and it's over.
content.location: On a small boulder visible from the road next to Don't Rock the Boat. Just to the left of the trail leading to Uncertainty Principle.

content.description: Got soles?  Sliding off of this boulder problem is safe but uses up your shoes.  On the trail to Uncertainty Principle, to one's right is this short seam.  Fun and safe.
This route starts as Uncertainty Principle, but traverses left towards a bolt.  From here it heads up to finish the same.  Not often done.

climbs.name: The Joker
climbs.fa: Rick Allenby and Ron Amick, March 1988

content.description: Dicey, delicate moves out of a depression to reach a flake and huck for the top
content.location: Around the corner to the left of Big Nose and Fly by night. Starts in the obvious depression.

content.description: This the very hard face climb just right of Eric's Crack.

Start on far right side of flake, traverse a couple moves and gun to the lip.  A shorter variation exists, start with hands on right facing sidepulls. Climb is then two moves and a bit easier.

Video:

vimeo.com/38012966
content.protection: Pads, not tall with a pretty good landing.
content.location: Visible from road, just downhill from the painted boulders, boulder has a small capstone on top.

content.description: Steep, reachy face climbing
content.location: This is the dark streak 10 feet left of Big Nose

content.description: This is the offwidth splitter located on the backside of the big boulder, a few yards left of the Mr. Snoid boulder.  A big tree is on the side that a climber would see from the road.

Don't let the rating or the short nature of this climb fool you.  This is a stout thin fingers crack that is plain and simply absent of feet.  It is located on the right side of the road just past

Rock The Boat

.
content.protection: Small cams/nuts sets this up as a TR, and once in a while as a boulder problem.

content.description: Start with a high reach, left hand on the sharp knob and crank!

Start matched on the middle of the “Full Circle” rail, dyno to the lip.

https://youtu.be/rYlyY7STrtk
content.location: Full circle boulder, just in from the painted boulders.

content.description: Three obvious cracks. The left and right cracks are finger width. The middle crack is off width.
content.protection: Pretty safe to just boulder these.
content.location: This boulder is located across from Don't Rock the Boat. It's on the east side of the road. The trail leading down to the Robbins Boulder begins at the north end of this boulder, just south of the power lines.

content.description: This little gem is yet another Woodson sole stealer.  Smear and palm your way up the left corner of this short roadside problem
content.location: On the righthand side of the switchback for the Uncertainty Principle.  Short, rounded, basically nondescript boulder.

content.description: Start matched on the left most hold on the horizontal seam and traverse right keeping your feet low. The crux is pulling over the lip/bulge. Once over the lip follow the thin edges via the most logical route to the summit. Easy down climb off the back.
content.location: The climb starts on the paved road. Make sure to keep your gear out of the way as much as possible for passing hikers. Expect a crowd to stop and watch.

content.description:
Man, what a gem. Purely round. Start on slopers with feet in the seam, pull up and over the bulge. No jumping.

This may be something different, it's unclear where the actual "Anticlimax Mantle" is on the boulder.
content.location: On the slug of a boulder next to Bobby Brown Arete.

content.description: Short and stout. Lieback and crimp your way up this seam with really bad feet through the crux. Have your calluses built up for this one, the top crimps are sharp.Kevin Powell visited Woodson and sent this unclimbed Woodson local project in tennis shoes and cheekily said, "it's 10a, on the outside".
content.protection:
Gear in the horizontal.

.5-1 and bring something to extend the anchor about 7 feet.
content.location: Past Lie Detector and before the Painted Boulder.  On the left side of the road about 20 feet into the bushes.  The climb is at the base of the huge "flat top" looking boulder that can be seen from the Painted Boulder switchback.  Faces west.
